","17 May 1519":"17 May 1519","29 May 1531":"29 May 1531","1561":"1561","1571":"1571","1581":"1581","1580":"1580","1590":"1590","26 September 1561":"26 September 1561","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1533":"1533","1498":"1498","1531":"1531","1574":"1574","Abt. 1530":"1530","24 December 1574":"24 December 1574","1519":"1519","1506":"1506","1549":"1549","Guildford, Surrey, England":"Guildford, Surrey, England","Great Bromley, Essex, England":"Great Bromley, Essex, England","Albury, Guildford, Surrey, England, United Kingdom":"Albury, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":29,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":38,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":49,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":51,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Morthdon was born on 17 May 1519, in Guildford, Surrey, England, her father, Richard William Morthdon, was 21 and her mother, Agnes Millington, was 21. She married John Alfred Farley in 1530, in Great Bromley, Essex, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died on 24 December 1574, in Great Bromley, Essex, England, at the age of 55."},"et":{"17 May 1519–24 December 1574":"17. mai 1519–24. detsember 1574","1519–1574":"1519–1574","1506–1581":"1506–1581","1531–1561":"1531–1561","1533–Male":"1533–Surnud","1535–Male":"1535–Surnud","1498–1580":"1498–1580","1498–1590":"1498–1590","17 May 1519":"17. mai 1519","29 May 1531":"29. mai 1531","1561":"1561","1571":"1571","1581":"1581","1580":"1580","1590":"1590","26 September 1561":"26. september 1561","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1533":"1533","1498":"1498","1531":"1531","1574":"1574","Abt. 1530":"1530","24 December 1574":"24. detsember 1574","1519":"1519","1506":"1506","1549":"1549","Guildford, Surrey, England":"Guildfor